  <div class="lead-card">
    <div>
      <div class="lead-tag">Lead · Aftermarket Report · Wednesday 2 April 2026</div>
      <h3 class="lead-hl">Nifty opened FY27 with a 568-point gap-up at 22,899 — the biggest single-day open in months — driven by Trump signalling a possible deal with a "more reasonable regime" in Iran. By close, it had given back nearly all of it, settling at 22,679. But the breadth told a completely different story: 2,936 advances vs just 283 declines. The market went up broadly. The index didn't hold.</h3>
      <p class="lead-summary">Well, you see, this is what a market looks like when macro uncertainty is high but risk appetite is quietly recovering. The Nifty itself faced a ceiling — Max Call OI sat at 23,000, creating a hard resistance band at 23,100–23,200 that the index ran straight into and bounced off. In the afternoon, as the initial euphoria of a possible Iran deal faded without any concrete announcement, selling picked up and the index slid from 22,900 to 22,650 before recovering to 22,679 at close. Not a pretty close. But the broader market — the 2,936 stocks that went up versus the 283 that fell — was telling a different story. This breadth reading is the best since late February. It suggests that the Monday FY26-end selloff was a capitulation, not the beginning of a new leg lower. That said, the April 6 Iran deadline is still four days away. No structural resolution has happened. The gap-up was priced on a tweet, not a treaty.</p>
      <p class="lead-summary" style="margin-top:0.6rem">The day's standout sector was defence — up nearly 6% on the Nifty India Defence Index. The trigger was Trump's statement hinting at exiting NATO ("beyond reconsideration... I always knew they were a paper tiger"), combined with Rajnath Singh clearing defence deals worth ₹2.38 lakh crore in one shot. Put simply, a US retreating from NATO means Europe needs to rearm fast, India needs to self-defend faster, and every domestic defence manufacturer looks structurally re-rated. PSU Bank was also a top gainer at +3.70%. Pharma was the sole sector in red (-0.99%). Source: Aftermarket Report.</p>
