      <div class="card-deck">The government hiked commercial LPG (19kg cylinder used by restaurants, hotels, caterers) by ₹195.5 to ₹2,078.5 in Delhi — a 10% increase, the largest single hike since the Iran war began. This follows the government's logic: commercial users have more pricing flexibility than household consumers, and the OMC underrecoveries on LPG (currently about ₹380 per cylinder) cannot be sustained indefinitely. Aviation Turbine Fuel (ATF) for international and chartered flights more than doubled — jet fuel is priced at import parity and not subsidised. Domestic flights got a cap: ATF price increase for scheduled domestic carriers was limited to 25%. IndiGo, SpiceJet, and Air India have been managing rising fuel costs for five weeks; the domestic cap provides partial relief while international routes absorb the full market rate. Source: Aftermarket Report.</div>
