      <div class="card-deck">Willie Walsh is one of the most respected airline executives in the world. He ran Aer Lingus, turned around British Airways, built International Airlines Group (IAG — the parent of BA, Iberia, Vueling), and then became Director General of IATA. His appointment as IndiGo's CEO is a signal that the board wants serious crisis-management and network-scaling experience at the top. IndiGo has been under severe pressure: fuel costs have spiked 25%+ for domestic operations, the Iran war has disrupted Middle East routes (a key market for the airline), and the exit of previous CEO Pieter Elbers left a leadership gap. Walsh's track record at British Airways — where he navigated post-9/11 collapse, multiple fuel crises, and Labour union disputes — is exactly the kind of experience IndiGo needs right now. Due to this, IndiGo shares were in focus on the news, even as the broader airline sector remained under fuel cost pressure. Source: Aftermarket Report.</div>
