      <div class="card-deck">NSE's launch of exchange-traded natural gas futures — in collaboration with Indian Gas Exchange (IGX) — is a genuinely significant market infrastructure development that arrived on the exact day it mattered most: FY27 Day 1, as India pushes an emergency pivot from LPG to piped natural gas. Back in the day, natural gas price discovery in India happened through bilateral contracts and import benchmarks (Henry Hub in the US, TTF in Europe) — there was no Indian domestic gas price benchmark. GIXI (Gas IndeX of India) tracks actual domestic gas trades across six regional delivery hubs, giving a real price signal for Indian gas. Exchange-traded derivatives on this benchmark allow city gas distributors, industrial consumers, fertilizer companies, and power plants to hedge their natural gas costs for the first time. This is particularly relevant now — with the government forcing a rapid scale-up of PNG connections and commercial users shifting to domestic gas, having a liquid derivatives market to manage the price risk is not an optional add-on. It is infrastructure. Source: Aftermarket Report.</div>
