      <h3 class="lead-hl">You have an LPG cylinder at home as a backup, even though you have a piped gas connection. The government has now told you to surrender that cylinder within 90 days — or lose your cooking fuel supply entirely. This is not a gentle nudge. It is an emergency energy reallocation order under the Essential Commodities Act. Well, let's find out why India is doing this now, and why it is harder than it sounds.</h3>
      <p class="lead-summary">Back in the day, India's cooking fuel policy was simple: Ujjwala for the rural poor (LPG cylinders at subsidised rates), PNG for urban households who could access it, and the rest managed through market mechanisms. The Iran war ended that simplicity. India imports approximately 60% of its LPG, and roughly 90% of those imports transit the Strait of Hormuz. When the strait closed, cylinder booking gaps stretched to 45 days and black market prices hit ₹4,000 per cylinder. The government's response: issue an order under the Essential Commodities Act directing Oil Marketing Companies — Indian Oil, BPCL, HPCL — to digitally map all addresses and automatically block LPG cylinder bookings for any household where PNG is available.</p>
      <p class="lead-summary" style="margin-top:0.6rem">The scale of the problem is the problem. India has 33 crore LPG connections and just 1.6 crore PNG connections — roughly 5% of households. Even if the 1.6 crore PNG households surrender their cylinders immediately, that frees up a relatively small portion of LPG demand. The bigger structural issue is this: India has essentially zero strategic LPG reserves. Total underground storage holds about 1,40,000 metric tonnes. Daily consumption is roughly 90,000 tonnes. That is less than two days of buffer. Compare that to crude oil, where India holds approximately 72 days of combined strategic and commercial reserves. The reason the government is pushing PNG so hard is not just supply chain diversification — it is about structural reserve buffer. Natural gas is half-domestically produced (from ONGC, Oil India, and the Reliance-BP KG-D6 venture) and has more diversified import contracts (Australia, US). A single chokepoint like Hormuz cannot kill India's gas supply the way it can kill its LPG supply. Source: Daily Brief (Zerodha).</p>
