      <div class="card-deck">You got a credit card approved in minutes. A personal loan with three taps. A buy-now-pay-later option on every checkout page. That frictionless access to credit that felt like progress — Finshots today asks whether it is quietly building the next wave of banking stress. Active credit cards in India: 100 million as of December 2024, up 5x from FY12. The structural risk is the time lag: unsecured loan stress appears 18–36 months after disbursement. Credit card NPAs jumped 73% in FY22 and another 28% in FY24 — meaning loans originated in 2019–21 are now defaulting. The current wave of easy credit (2022–24) has not yet fully seasoned into its default cycle. Banks are tightening at the margins: IDFC First cut its MFI book from 6.6% to 2.4% of total loans; credit card rewards are being cut, fees adjusted, low-value users being de-prioritised. But the central tension remains: banks are still growing unsecured credit because economic growth supports repayment — as long as incomes keep pace. The risk is not an imminent crisis. It is a structural vulnerability that would amplify any income shock. And the Iran war is an income shock for the segments of the economy most likely to be carrying unsecured debt: daily wage workers, small traders, self-employed professionals. Source: Finshots.</div>
