      <div class="card-deck">India's electrical cables and wires sector has been one of the biggest structural winners of the infrastructure boom — Polycab Industries surged from ₹400 to ₹6,000+ in five years, KEI Industries and RR Kabel followed similar trajectories. Finolex Cables had the oldest brand, the strongest balance sheet, and the earliest market position. It still missed the supercycle. The Ken's Long & Short analysis identifies three compounding factors: margin compression from a project-heavy revenue mix (institutional wiring contracts for construction projects carry thin margins, unlike the B2C retail cables business that competitors focused on), slower operational scaling versus peers who were more aggressively building distribution, and a reluctance to expand aggressively into the higher-margin product categories (flexible cables, specialty cables, communication cables) that drove peers' earnings quality. The cautionary lesson: in a structural sector boom, being the established incumbent is not the same thing as being the best-positioned company. Source: The Ken.</div>
