    <div>
      <div class="lead-tag">Deep Read · Daily Brief (Zerodha) · 2 April 2026</div>
      <h3 class="lead-hl">To make things easier to grasp, think of LPG and PNG as two completely different fuels that happen to do the same job in your kitchen. LPG is propane and butane — compressed into liquid, delivered in red steel cylinders, produced in the Gulf, transited through Hormuz. PNG is primarily methane — delivered through underground pipes, partly produced domestically, and with more diversified import sources. India has spent 30 years building LPG infrastructure for 33 crore households. It now has 90 days to redirect that demand through 1.6 crore PNG connections.</h3>
      <p class="lead-summary">The chemistry matters here before the politics. LPG has roughly 2.5 times the energy density per cubic metre compared to natural gas. This creates the hot, intense, instantly adjustable flame that Indian cooking demands — the split-second blast for a tadka, the sustained high heat under a kadhai, the rapid toggle between high and low for a phulka. PNG's flame is gentler and slower to respond. Most Indians who convert from LPG to PNG simply drill out the gas jets on their existing LPG stoves — which drops thermal efficiency and can produce unsafe carbon monoxide levels. A proper conversion costs ₹2,000–5,000. This is not a trivial friction for 1.6 crore households being asked to switch.</p>
      <p class="lead-summary" style="margin-top:0.6rem">But the government's strategic calculus is sound. India has zero fallback if Hormuz stays closed for LPG — just 1,40,000 metric tonnes of underground storage against 90,000 tonnes daily consumption. Less than two days of buffer. For natural gas, the picture is genuinely different: roughly half is produced domestically, and import contracts are spread across the US, Australia, and Qatar. The PNGRB also completed a critical infrastructure reform in January 2026: a unified tariff structure that collapsed regional pricing disparities, cutting transportation costs for distant areas by nearly 50%. This makes PNG economically viable in cities that were previously priced out. The hard constraint is physical: India has only laid sufficient last-mile pipeline to serve approximately 1.6 crore connections out of a 12.63 crore target. APM gas (domestically produced at capped prices, which subsidises city gas distribution economics) is also declining — legacy fields expected to peak now and fall 20% by 2030. The more PNG connections India adds, the more imported LNG it will need to fill them. That shifts dependency from Hormuz-LPG to LNG-terminals — a better risk profile, but still an import dependency. India isn't eliminating a supply chain vulnerability. It is diversifying from one to another. Source: Daily Brief (Zerodha).</p>
