    <div class="card" onclick="openM('lpg-png-deep')">
      <span class="ctag blue">Deep Read · Energy</span>
      <div class="card-hl">The full LPG to PNG story — why the government is right about the direction and wrong about the timeline</div>
      <div class="card-deck">The government's LPG-to-PNG pivot is strategically correct for three reasons. First, supply chain diversification: LPG has a single chokepoint (Hormuz), no strategic reserve, and a Gulf-concentrated supplier base. PNG has partial domestic production, more diversified LNG contracts, and a physically different supply chain that doesn't depend on cylinder tankers. Second, the unified tariff reform (January 2026): by collapsing the additive regional tariff structure into two flat zones, the PNGRB made PNG economically viable in cities like Bengaluru and Hyderabad that were previously paying 2–3x the tariff of consumers near Gujarat gas sources. Third, the Hormuz crisis created the social permission for a switch that 30 years of policy couldn't. When cylinder booking takes 45 days and black market prices are ₹4,000, consumers are finally willing to spend ₹2,000–5,000 to properly convert their stoves. That said, the direction is right but the timeline is not. India needs to lay last-mile pipelines to cover the gap between 1.6 crore active connections and the 6 crore LPG households who live in areas where PNG pipelines technically exist but don't reach their specific building. That is a 3–5 year infrastructure task, not a 90-day one. The government's order is best read as a demand management tool — freeing up LPG cylinder capacity for households and commercial users who genuinely cannot access PNG — rather than a realistic plan to move 33 crore connections to PNG in three months. Source: Daily Brief (Zerodha).</div>
