      <div class="card-deck">The Daily Brief's tidbits include two significant manufacturing announcements. First, the Electronics Component Manufacturing Scheme (ECMS): the government approved 75 projects totalling ₹61,671 crore in investment — overshooting the scheme's original ₹59,350 crore target. The standout approval: India's first rare earth permanent magnet manufacturing facility, using rare-earth oxides, at ₹700 crore investment. India currently imports 85–90% of its rare earth magnets from China — and these magnets are critical inputs for EV motors, wind turbines, defence systems, and consumer electronics. Other ECMS approvals: ₹1,683 crore for capital goods, ₹1,350 crore for display module sub-assemblies, ₹500 crore for lithium-ion cells. Second, Micron's second semiconductor plant in India was inaugurated on March 31 — just 19 months after groundwork began, and only 49 days after the first plant was inaugurated on February 10. IT Minister Ashwini Vaishnaw called the pace "a demonstration of India's manufacturing capability." Source: Daily Brief (Zerodha).</div>
