  "gaar-maruti": {
    tag:"Markets · Policy",
    hl:"GAAR clarification for pre-2017 investments + Maruti March sales +16.72%",
    src:"Aftermarket Report",
    url:"https://aftermarketreport.zerodha.com/p/positive-global-cues-lift-nifty-near",
    body:`<p>Two quick but meaningful market notes. GAAR — the General Anti-Avoidance Rule — allows the Income Tax Department to disregard transactions it considers to be structured primarily for tax avoidance rather than commercial substance. Since its implementation in 2017, it has created an overhang for foreign PE and VC firms that made investments in India through structures set up before that date — structures that were legal when created but might be scrutinised under GAAR on exit. The government's clarification that GAAR will not apply to exits from pre-April 2017 investments removes this uncertainty cleanly. Well, this matters now because FII sentiment toward India has been negative through the Iran war. A clear, investor-friendly regulatory signal — especially one that affects the PE and VC community directly — is a meaningful relationship maintenance gesture at a sensitive time. Maruti Suzuki's March numbers were strong in the context: 2,25,251 total units (+16.72% YoY), with domestic PV at 1,66,219 (+10.27%). The numbers show that consumer demand for passenger vehicles held firm through the war's first five weeks — the higher-ticket, considered-purchase nature of cars means demand is more resilient to short-term uncertainty than discretionary consumer goods. Maruti's strong sales also validate the premiumisation narrative: the company's SUV lineup (Brezza, Grand Vitara, Jimny) was the primary driver. Source: Aftermarket Report.</p>`
  },
  "fy26-auto-review": {
    tag:"ETAuto · FY26 Review",
    hl:"FY26 India auto: records despite a war — the full story",
    src:"ETAuto",
    url:"https://auto.economictimes.indiatimes.com",
    body:`<p>FY26's auto story has a very specific shape when you plot it month by month. April through September 2025 were sluggish: a cautious consumer, elevated dealer inventory, patchy rural demand, and no clear demand catalyst. The industry grew, but modestly. Then October 2025 to February 2026 was the acceleration phase: the festive season came with strong pent-up demand, premiumisation continued at pace, and EV penetration picked up gradually. Then the Iran war arrived on February 28 and did something unexpected to the numbers: it turbo-charged EV adoption in the last five weeks of FY26. When petrol prices rose, CNG pumps started running dry, and LPG cylinders became scarce, the total cost of ownership argument for an EV — which had always been theoretically correct — became viscerally obvious to consumers who were already on the fence. The result: March 2026 e2W sales of approximately 1.7 lakh units, up 36% YoY. Passenger vehicle volumes hit all-time annual highs. And the industry entered FY27 at record levels across most segments. The question the industry is now wrestling with: how much of this was structural (premiumisation, income growth) versus accidental (war-driven cost shock accelerating decisions that were going to happen anyway over 18 months)? If the Iran situation resolves in April, does some of the EV demand pull forward to the next 12 months disappear? The honest answer is yes — partially. The structural drivers remain. The accidental acceleration may not. Source: ETAuto.</p>`
  },
  "e2w-march-record": {
    tag:"ETAuto · EV 2W",
    hl:"Electric 2W sales +36% in March — fuel shortage fears, end-of-fiscal discounts, and a structural shift",
    src:"ETAuto",
    url:"https://auto.economictimes.indiatimes.com",
    body:`<p>To make things easier to grasp, the 36% YoY jump in electric 2-wheeler sales in March 2026 has three distinct drivers that all amplified each other. First: end-of-fiscal inventory push. OEMs always push hard in March to meet annual targets. This year, the incentive was sharper than normal because FY27 brings higher import costs (rupee at ₹95, component prices rising) that will force price hikes on many models. Dealers and consumers who knew prices were going up had strong reason to transact in March. Second: fuel shortage fears. With petrol structurally expensive, CNG pressure low at Mumbai pumps, and LPG cylinders scarce, the immediate operational economics of an electric scooter became unambiguous. Not only this — the government's LPG-to-PNG order (surrender cylinders in 90 days) created psychological urgency: if cooking gas is being rationed, motoring fuel might be next. That psychology — even without actual rationing of petrol — drove some consumers from the consideration phase to the purchase phase for EVs. Third: structural demand. India's EV 2W penetration was already growing before the war. Ola Electric, TVS iQube, Bajaj Chetak, and Ather had all expanded their model ranges and distribution in FY26. The war accelerated a trend that existed, rather than creating one from scratch. Ather's positioning specifically benefits: the oil price shock makes its ₹1 lakh+ premium feel less like a luxury and more like a rational investment in fuel-cost insulation. Source: ETAuto.</p>`
  },
  "fy27-auto-headwinds": {
    tag:"ETAuto · FY27 Headwinds",
    hl:"West Asia war headwinds for India auto in FY27 — the five pressures OEMs are entering with",
    src:"ETAuto",
    url:"https://auto.economictimes.indiatimes.com",
    body:`<p>ETAuto's FY27 headwinds analysis identifies five compounding pressures that India's auto industry is entering the new financial year with. First, rising fuel costs inflate the entire supply chain. Plastics (petrochemical-derived), rubber (energy-intensive to produce), logistics (diesel-dependent), and components shipped by air all cost more when oil is at $100+. This is before the rupee effect. Second, the rupee at ₹95.22 is a direct margin hit on every imported component. Semiconductors (priced in dollars), display panels (Taiwan), precision electronics (Japan, Germany) — these are core inputs that India's OEMs cannot yet fully source domestically. A 10–12% currency depreciation over FY26 means those imported components are equivalently more expensive. Third, car prices are going up. Tata Motors, BMW India, and Mercedes-Benz India have all announced FY27 price hikes. This creates a short-term pull-forward of demand (consumers buying in March before hikes land) followed by demand softness in Q1 FY27. Fourth, NBFC stress in vehicle loans. Nomura data highlights rising NPA pressure in MSME and vehicle financing portfolios — a direct consequence of income stress in fuel-sensitive segments of the economy. When auto NBFCs tighten underwriting or raise rates, volumes in tier 2/3 markets — which are credit-dependent — slow. Fifth, the CNG infrastructure strain: autorickshaw drivers in Mumbai suburbs are already flagging low CNG pressure at pumps. If CNG vehicles become operationally unreliable in Q1 FY27, the commercial 3-wheeler and taxi segments could face a sharp demand drop, with demand either waiting out the supply issue or converting to EVs. Source: ETAuto.</p>`
  },
  "wto-crisis": {
    tag:"Daily Brief · Trade",
    hl:"The WTO's 14th ministerial conference failed — India's role, the e-commerce moratorium lapse, and what comes next",
    src:"Daily Brief (Zerodha)",
    url:"https://thedailybrief.zerodha.com/p/india-wants-to-switch-from-lpg-to",
    body:`<p>Back in the day — 1995 to be precise — the WTO was founded on a specific theory of how global trade should work: that divorcing trade from raw power and establishing rules-based predictability would make everyone better off. For 30 years, this theory delivered modest but real results. Now all four of its pillars are in various stages of failure. The norm-setting pillar: in 30 years, the WTO produced only two multilateral agreements. The Doha Development Agenda, launched in 2001 with promises to developing countries on agriculture and services, is dead in all but name. The dispute settlement pillar: the appellate body has had zero members since 2020, after the US blocked new appointments under both Trump and Biden. Countries can simply appeal adverse panel rulings into an indefinite void. The enforcement pillar: the 2026 US Trade Policy Agenda explicitly called the Most-Favoured Nation principle "not just unsuitable for this era" but actively harmful. The transparency pillar: more than half of WTO members failed to submit required subsidy notifications by 2023. The 14th Ministerial Conference in Yaoundé was supposed to produce a reform roadmap. Instead: the e-commerce moratorium — a 1998 rule banning customs duties on digital trade flows — was not renewed for the first time. India wanted it ended; the US wanted it permanent; they compromised on a two-year extension; Brazil then blocked even that. For the first time since 1998, countries are technically free to tax cross-border digital flows. India stood alone against 129 members on the IFD investment facilitation agreement, blocking it on procedural grounds (old issues must be resolved before new frameworks are added). The DG ended the conference by saying "the world order and multilateral system we used to know has irrevocably changed… we will not get it back." Source: Daily Brief (Zerodha).</p>`
  },
  "finshots-banks": {
    tag:"Finshots · Banking",
    hl:"The Indian bank credit stress that's building slowly in the background",
    src:"Finshots",
    url:"https://finshots.in",
    body:`<p>You see, unsecured lending has a specific and predictable failure pattern. In the early stages of a credit cycle, defaults are low, confidence is high, and banks expand further. The risk builds quietly — because unsecured loan stress appears 18–36 months after disbursement, not immediately. Credit card NPAs surged 73% in FY22 and then another 28% in FY24 — meaning loans originated during the 2019–21 easy-money period are now defaulting at scale. The current wave of aggressive unsecured lending happened in 2022–24. Its stress cycle hasn't fully matured yet. By 2025–26, we will be in the window where those loans begin defaulting. India's banks are not ignoring this. The RBI increased risk weights on unsecured loans in late 2024, forcing banks to hold more capital against every rupee of unsecured credit. IDFC First Bank has aggressively reduced its microfinance (MFI) book from 6.6% to 2.4% of total loans. Credit card issuers are cutting rewards and de-prioritising high-risk users. But the systemic tension remains: banks continue growing unsecured credit because economic growth supports repayment — as long as incomes keep pace with borrowing. The Iran war creates exactly the kind of income shock that could break this equation for certain segments. Not only this — the recovery rate on unsecured defaults is structurally lower than on secured loans (no collateral to auction). When these loans go bad, more of the loss flows directly to bank P&Ls. The concern Finshots raises is not an imminent crisis — India's banking system is better capitalised than in the 2015–19 NPA crisis era. It is a structural vulnerability that would amplify any further macro deterioration. Source: Finshots.</p>`
  },
  "ken-sovereign-ai": {
    tag:"The Ken · AI · Policy",
    hl:"India's two sovereign AI programmes — the official one with unused GPUs and the private one with $600mn in debt",
    src:"The Ken",
    url:"https://the-ken.com/story/india-has-two-sovereign-ai-programmes-one-is-official-the-other-isnt/",
    body:`<p>To make things easier to grasp, sovereign AI compute means this: a country's AI applications run on GPUs that the country owns and controls, rather than on data centres owned by US hyperscalers (Amazon AWS, Microsoft Azure, Google Cloud). The argument for sovereign compute: data sovereignty (sensitive Indian data doesn't leave India), strategic autonomy (India isn't dependent on US cloud access for critical AI infrastructure), and economic value capture (the margin from running AI workloads stays in India). Neysa's $1.2 billion raise — $600 million equity from Blackstone-led investors, $600 million in debt — is the private sector's bet on this thesis. They want to procure 20,000 Nvidia GPUs, deploy them in Indian data centres, and sell compute access to Indian AI startups and enterprises at roughly ₹65 per GPU-hour (cheap by global standards). The Ken's critical insight: even the official IndiaAI Mission's GPUs — government-procured, government-subsidised, supposed to be the most attractive option for Indian AI developers — are 22% unutilised. E2E Networks, India's only listed AI cloud provider (backed by Larsen & Toubro), has seen GPU utilisation fall sharply in recent quarters. The demand problem: India's AI startup ecosystem is growing rapidly, but the companies that would use GPU compute at scale are either too early-stage to need it at volume, or they are already using US hyperscaler cloud credits (which come with startup programmes, tooling, and engineering support that Indian domestic cloud providers cannot match). Building supply before demand exists is not a new Indian policy failure. The Ken's uncomfortable comparison: BSNL built towers, Jio had to come and generate the demand. The question is whether India's AI applications ecosystem develops fast enough to fill the compute Neysa and IndiaAI Mission are building. Source: The Ken.</p>`
  },
  "finolex-missed": {
    tag:"The Ken · Stocks",
    hl:"Finolex Cables missed India's cable boom — thinning margins, project mix, and faster-scaling peers",
    src:"The Ken",
    url:"https://the-ken.com/long_and_short/finolex-cables-had-the-money-the-brand-the-market-and-still-missed-the-boom/",
    body:`<p>Back in the day, if you wanted electrical cables in India, Finolex was the name. Founded in 1958, the Pune-based company built the strongest brand in India's wires and cables industry through decades of presence in retail hardware stores, electrician relationships, and quality reputation. When India's infrastructure and real estate boom created a massive tailwind for cables demand in the early 2020s, Finolex had first-mover advantage in brand, distribution, and balance sheet. Polycab, which listed in 2019, had none of Finolex's brand legacy. KEI Industries was smaller. RR Kabel was newer. And yet: Polycab went from ₹400 to ₹6,000+. KEI surged similarly. RR Kabel IPO'd at a premium in 2023 and has held strong. Finolex has underperformed all three by a significant margin. The Ken's Long & Short analysis identifies three compounding factors. First, revenue mix: Finolex has a higher share of project-based institutional sales (wiring for construction projects, infrastructure contracts) versus retail B2C sales. Project revenues are larger in ticket size but carry structurally thinner margins — the buyer is sophisticated and negotiates hard. Retail cables sold through hardware stores carry much better margins. Competitors focused more on the retail channel. Second, operational pace: peers scaled faster in distribution, dealer management, and capacity expansion. Finolex's more conservative balance sheet management slowed reinvestment. Third, product mix evolution: higher-margin specialty cables (flexible cables, instrumentation cables, communication cables) required faster product development cycles than Finolex moved at. The lesson The Ken draws: being the established leader in a structural boom is not sufficient. The winners were the ones who moved fastest, not the ones who started with the most advantages. Source: The Ken.</p>`
  },
  "lpg-png-deep": {
    tag:"Deep Read · Energy Policy",
    hl:"The LPG to PNG switch — why the government is right about direction and wrong about timeline",
    src:"Daily Brief (Zerodha)",
    url:"https://thedailybrief.zerodha.com/p/india-wants-to-switch-from-lpg-to",
    body:`<p>The government's 90-day LPG cylinder surrender order is best understood as three things simultaneously: an emergency demand management measure (freeing up LPG for households and users who genuinely cannot access PNG), a long-overdue policy acceleration (India has been trying to expand PNG for decades and the Hormuz crisis gave it the social permission that 30 years of policy couldn't), and an infrastructure problem that 90 days cannot solve. The fundamental physical constraint: India has only 1.6 crore active PNG connections against 33 crore LPG connections. Even if you focus only on the 6 crore LPG consumers who live in areas where PNG pipelines technically exist (per the Daily Brief), that still requires reaching them through last-mile connections that haven't been laid yet. Laying pipelines in dense urban areas requires permissions, digging through utility corridors packed with water, sewage, electricity, and telecom infrastructure, and in old buildings, structural work. Renters need landlord NOCs. Even once connected, just 63% of existing PNG connections are actually billing and live. The economics are improving: the PNGRB's January 2026 unified tariff reform cut transportation costs for distant areas by nearly 50%, making PNG genuinely price-competitive in markets like Bengaluru and Hyderabad that were previously unviable. And the government's strategic rationale is correct: India's LPG has a single Hormuz dependency with less than two days of strategic reserve. PNG has partial domestic production and diversified import contracts. But the 90-day deadline is a political signal, not an operational plan. The realistic timeline for meaningful PNG expansion is 3–5 years. What the government can do in 90 days is identify the most accessible households (already in PNG-serviced areas, ground-floor access, cooperative landlords) and aggressively connect them. The rest requires the infrastructure to be built first. Source: Daily Brief (Zerodha).</p>`
  },
  "semiconductor-ecms": {
    tag:"India · Semiconductors",
    hl:"ECMS: 75 projects, ₹61,671 crore, India's first rare earth magnet plant — and Micron's second fab inaugurated",
    src:"Daily Brief (Zerodha)",
    url:"https://thedailybrief.zerodha.com/p/india-wants-to-switch-from-lpg-to",
    body:`<p>The Electronics Component Manufacturing Scheme (ECMS) approvals announced in the Daily Brief's tidbits section deserve more attention than the format allows. 75 projects, ₹61,671 crore in investment — which actually exceeded the scheme's original ₹59,350 crore target. The standout: India's first rare earth permanent magnet manufacturing facility, approved at ₹700 crore. Why does this matter? India currently imports 85–90% of its rare earth permanent magnets from China. These magnets — made from elements like neodymium and dysprosium — are essential for EV motors (every electric vehicle uses them), wind turbine generators, defence guidance systems, industrial robots, and consumer electronics like smartphones and speakers. China controls roughly 85% of global rare earth magnet production and has used this dominance as geopolitical leverage (restricting exports to Japan in 2010, threatening restrictions on the US during trade disputes). India building its first rare earth magnet plant is a strategic supply chain diversification from single-country dependence in a material that sits at the intersection of electrification, decarbonisation, and defence. Not only this — other ECMS approvals fill out important parts of India's electronics manufacturing puzzle: ₹1,683 crore for capital goods (the machines that make the machines), ₹1,350 crore for display module sub-assemblies (screens for phones, monitors, vehicles), ₹500 crore for lithium-ion cells. Micron's second semiconductor plant inauguration on March 31 — 19 months after groundwork began, 49 days after the first plant's inauguration — shows that when India moves fast on semiconductor manufacturing, it can match the fastest timelines globally. Source: Daily Brief (Zerodha).</p>`
  },
  "iran-deal-signal": {
    tag:"Iran · Geopolitics",
    hl:"Brent -2% on Iran deal signal — what Trump said, what it means, and why markets stayed cautious",
    src:"Aftermarket Report",
    url:"https://aftermarketreport.zerodha.com/p/positive-global-cues-lift-nifty-near",
    body:`<p>Trump's statement about dealing with a "more reasonable regime" in Iran drove a 2% fall in Brent crude to approximately $102 — and a 568-point Nifty gap-up. But both moves unwound significantly during the session, reflecting markets' ambivalence about how real the deal signal is. The statement was characteristically vague. Trump simultaneously warned of "major strikes" on Iranian energy infrastructure if Hormuz isn't reopened, and suggested productive conversations are happening. There are no confirmed formal talks. US troop movements in the region continue. Iran's parliament is still drafting the Hormuz transit fee law — a law that, if enacted, would institutionalise Iran's control over the strait rather than cede it. The most credible diplomatic channel — Pakistan as intermediary for indirect talks — has produced tangible but limited results: individual Indian tanker passages through the IRGC-controlled corridor, some Gulf shipping exemptions for certain flag states. None of this amounts to a structural resolution. Brent at $102 is still $39 above the pre-war level of $63. No supply chain relief has actually arrived. The market's read seems correct: this was a posture shift, not a policy shift. The April 6 deadline — Trump's explicit ultimatum for Iran to reopen the Strait or face strikes — is now four days away. Source: Aftermarket Report.</p>`
  },
  "nvidia-marvell": {
    tag:"Tech · AI · Semiconductors",
    hl:"Nvidia's $2bn investment in Marvell — custom AI silicon, India's chip design centres, and the hyperscaler hedge",
    src:"Aftermarket Report",
    url:"https://aftermarketreport.zerodha.com/p/positive-global-cues-lift-nifty-near",
    body:`<p>To understand why Nvidia investing $2 billion in Marvell matters, you need to understand what hyperscalers have been doing to Nvidia for the last three years. Google's TPU, Amazon's Trainium and Inferentia, Microsoft's Maia, Meta's MTIA — all are custom AI chips designed to reduce dependence on Nvidia's standard GPU lineup. They don't need to outperform Nvidia's H100 or H200 across all workloads; they just need to be good enough at specific workloads (training large models, running inference at scale) while being cheaper to buy and operate. Marvell specialises in designing these custom ASICs for hyperscalers. If Marvell chips replace some Nvidia GPUs in hyperscaler data centres, that's a direct revenue threat to Nvidia. So Nvidia's $2 billion investment in Marvell is a hedge: by owning a stake, Nvidia participates in the custom silicon wave even if it eats into its own standard GPU market. Marvell jumped 12% on the news. Nvidia was up 1.5% pre-market. The India angle: Marvell has one of its largest chip design centres in Pune — thousands of engineers designing these custom ASICs. Any acceleration in custom AI chip demand from hyperscalers flows directly through Marvell's Pune operations, which means more high-paying engineering jobs, more chip design work, and India's position in the global semiconductor value chain moves up. Source: Aftermarket Report.</p>`
  },
  "oracle-layoffs": {
    tag:"Tech · IT · Layoffs",
    hl:"Oracle 30,000 layoffs — ~12,000 in India. The enterprise IT restructuring wave and what it means for Bengaluru",
    src:"Aftermarket Report",
    url:"https://aftermarketreport.zerodha.com/p/positive-global-cues-lift-nifty-near",
    body:`<p>Oracle's layoff of approximately 30,000 employees globally — with around 12,000 in India — is one of the largest tech sector job cut announcements of 2026, following a wave that has included Salesforce, SAP, Intel, and others. Another round is reportedly expected within a month. The strategic context: Oracle has been pivoting aggressively toward AI-powered cloud services, autonomous database management, and generative AI applications. These products automate workflows that Oracle previously staffed with large engineering, QA, and support teams. The company is essentially rebuilding its workforce from a large-labour model (lots of people doing repetitive software engineering and database management tasks) to a smaller-but-higher-skills model (AI running the routine work, humans managing and extending it). India is disproportionately affected because Oracle's Indian operations are concentrated in exactly the roles being automated: software engineers, QA testers, support engineers, database administrators. Oracle's Bengaluru campus in particular is one of the company's largest outside the US. The second-order effects are significant. Bengaluru's apartment rental market, restaurant economy, and retail spending are meaningfully influenced by IT sector employment. Large-scale layoffs by Oracle — combined with layoffs from other IT companies facing similar AI automation pressures — create a local demand shock in Bengaluru that extends beyond the directly affected employees. Not only this — the announcement is a signal to every other enterprise software company: the AI restructuring wave has reached scale, and no function previously considered safe from automation is actually safe. Source: Aftermarket Report.</p>`
  },
  "global-bright-spots": {
    tag:"Global · Economy",
    hl:"Eurozone PMI 51.6 (strongest since June 2022) + South Korea exports +48.3% — the signals that cut against the doom narrative",
    src:"Aftermarket Report",
    url:"https://aftermarketreport.zerodha.com/p/positive-global-cues-lift-nifty-near",
    body:`<p>Two global data points deserve attention for pushing back against the dominant war-and-stagflation narrative. The S&P Global Eurozone Manufacturing PMI rose to 51.6 in March 2026 from 50.8 in February — the strongest expansion since June 2022. The interpretation is counterintuitive: the Iran war's supply disruptions are part of the reason for this improvement. Companies across Europe are building inventory buffers ahead of anticipated further disruption — front-loading orders, pulling forward purchases, and accelerating procurement. This temporarily boosts manufacturing output data even as underlying demand concerns remain. It is inventory-building activity, not a genuine acceleration in end consumer demand. But for European manufacturers — who were in contraction through 2024 and early 2025 — any expansion reading is meaningful. South Korea's exports surged 48.3% YoY in March 2026 to $86.13 billion — a new monthly record and the first time South Korea has exported more than $80 billion in a single month. Semiconductors led the jump significantly. This is a more straightforwardly positive signal: semiconductor exports track AI infrastructure investment, and the data suggests that despite the macro turbulence, hyperscalers and cloud providers are still investing at pace in AI capacity. Given that South Korea's TSMC-equivalent (Samsung, SK Hynix) produces memory chips that go into AI servers globally, this export data is a leading indicator that the AI build-out continues. Source: Aftermarket Report.</p>`
  }
